Amy M. Paten

Amy M. Paten is a British researcher who has made significant contributions to the field of healthcare research. This article outlines her notable work and association with East Kent Hospitals University NHS Foundation Trust. Early Career and Education

Paten pursued her undergraduate degree in Biological Sciences from the University of Kent, graduating in 2005. She then went on to earn her Master's degree in Public Health from the University of London in 2008. Her academic background laid the foundation for her future research endeavors. Research and Association with East Kent Hospitals University NHS Foundation Trust

Paten's research focus has primarily been on healthcare policy and patient outcomes. In 2010, she joined the East Kent Hospitals University NHS Foundation Trust as a research fellow, where she worked under the guidance of Dr. Sophia J. Patel, a renowned expert in healthcare research. During her tenure at the trust, Paten was involved in several studies that aimed to improve patient care and healthcare services. One of her notable works includes a study published in the Journal of Healthcare Research in 2012, titled "An Exploratory Study on Patient Satisfaction in Acute Care Settings." This study, which was conducted in collaboration with the trust, explored the factors influencing patient satisfaction in acute care settings and proposed recommendations for improvement. In 2014, Paten was part of a research team that investigated the impact of healthcare policy on patient outcomes. The study, titled "The Effect of Healthcare Policy on Patient Outcomes: A Systematic Review," was published in the International Journal of Healthcare Policy and Research. This study provided valuable insights into the relationship between healthcare policy and patient outcomes, informing policy decisions at the trust and beyond. Awards and Recognition

Paten's contributions to healthcare research have been recognized through several awards and honors. In 2015, she received the Early Career Researcher Award from the Royal College of Physicians for her outstanding work in healthcare research. References
